# Clean Code

> **DRAFT — starter content generated to satisfy CLAUDE.md's always-apply
> contract. Review and customize.**

## Names

- Names describe intent. `_falling_dims` is good; `_helper2` is not.
- Booleans read as predicates: `is_failing`, `has_misconceptions`, not
  `failing` or `misconceptions_bool`.
- Private helpers are `_prefixed`. Exported public surface is bare.
- No abbreviations except domain-standard ones (e.g. `pid` for persona id is
  OK because the codebase uses it everywhere).

## Function size

- A function does one thing. If you need an "and" in the docstring, split it.
- ~30 lines is a soft ceiling. Above 50, justify in a comment or split.
- Pure functions over side-effecting ones where possible. The evaluator and
  report renderers should not mutate state.

## Comments

- Comments explain **why**, not what. The code already shows what.
- A comment that restates a one-liner is noise — delete it.
- Docstrings on public functions state purpose + non-obvious contract,
  not the parameter types (those are in annotations).
- Inline `# noqa: <rule>` is allowed when justified by a short tail comment.

## Error handling

- Fail loud (CLAUDE.md Rule 11). Don't swallow exceptions silently.
- `try/except Exception: pass` requires a `# noqa` and a comment explaining
  why this is best-effort.
- Custom exception types only when callers need to discriminate; otherwise
  use stdlib (`ValueError`, `KeyError`, `RuntimeError`).
- Validation happens at boundaries (CLI args, env vars, HTTP inputs) and once
  validated, internal code can assume invariants.

## Formatting

- `ruff check` is law. `ruff format` is the formatter. Don't argue with it.
- Line length: 100 chars (set in `pyproject.toml`).
- Tests get `E501` ignored — long assertion messages are OK.

## Imports

- Top-of-module imports only. Deferred imports inside a function require a
  comment explaining the cycle being broken or the optional dependency being
  guarded.
- Group: stdlib, then third-party, then `.` local. Sorted alphabetically
  within each group.

## Type annotations

- Public functions and dataclass fields are annotated.
- Internal helpers may skip annotations when obvious; prefer them when
  signatures get complex.
- `from __future__ import annotations` at every file top so forward refs work.
